Let $A_0$ be the event the $n$ coins come up all heads.  Therefore $P(A_0)=2^{-n}$.
Let $B_ i$ be the event that just coin $i$ comes up tails and the other $n-1$ coins come up heads. Then $P(B_i)=2^{-n}$.
Also, let $B$ be the event that at most one of the coins comes up tails.  Therefore $B=A_ 0 \cup B_1 \cup B_2 \cup ... \cup B_ n$.
P($B$) = P($A_ 0 \cup B_1 \cup B_2 \cup ... \cup B_ n$)
The $A_0, B_1, ... B_n$ are mutually exclusive.
So P($B$) = $\frac{1}{2^n} + \frac{1}{2^n} + ... +  \frac{1}{2^n}$ ($n-1$ time)
Therefore P($B$) = $\frac{1}{2^n} + \frac{n-1}{2^n}$
Since P($B$) = $\frac{3}{16}$, $\frac{1}{2^n} + \frac{n-1}{2^n} = \frac{3}{16}$
Therefore, $2^{-n} (1+n-1) = \frac{3}{16}$
$log_2 (1+n-1) = log_2 \frac{3}{16}$
$log_2 (n) = log_2 \frac{3}{16}$
$n = \frac{3}{16}$
